European inflation fell on food
The accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the veritable increase in the price of food products.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording, after 2.6 per cent of October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent, the Union Statistics Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely to give a 3 percent - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuer banks, did not cut the basic interest, its assumption that the decrease, along with the price increases in raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to maintain the inflation rate below, but at least about two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not later have to intervene on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 per cent, recorded in Germany, struck the 12-year record, while in Spain it increased from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation was fired in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
Grain quotas increased by 88 per cent and soybean quotas have reached their maximum level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased by 52 per cent this year, reaching black gold last month almost $100 per barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from 2.1 per cent current to 2.5 per cent, instead of 2009 will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 or 4 months about 3 per cent, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
