In many hospitals saves with disinfectants
This year several thousand infections caused primarily by the improper application of antibiotics have been registered in hospitals.
Health conditions prevailing in hospitals, bed-laying and overloading of staff do not favour infection control - says the medical head of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many hospitals it is even saved with disinfectants.
Not long ago, a infection with MRSA has been diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of bacteria resistant to antibiotics was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A serious car accident was injured and the same patient had to return to the hospital shortly after having been infected with MRSA and since then there has been no significant surgical intervention by the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, cases of hospital infection by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance 1094 - said Karolina Böröcz, head of Department of National Epidemiology Centre.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been safely recorded, and there is no information.
About two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacilin.
One third of human beings carry in their nose the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) without causing any disease.
The infections caused by the SA (e.g., inflammation of the throat, amigdalitis, skin infections, infections of wounds) respond well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once applied excessively or improperly to antibiotics, bacteria that normally respond well to antibiotics become very resistant bacteria to antibiotics and are rapidly infected under inadequate hospital conditions.
Serious hospital infections, such as infections of wounds or septicaemia, may be caused primarily in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with weakened body, in the elderly or in those with low weight.
According to the medical director of Hospital János, there is nothing special about the MRSA infection, these infections are everyday in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotics resistant
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff take care of them in rubber and mask gloves and there are the appropriate antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are examined in advance to verify the presence of MRSA in your body, but not even so, infection can be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, but current national hospital conditions do not favour prevention of formation and infection with multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA into their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals there is no fashionable use of microbiological samples.
This fact is also due to the failure of the National Health Fund to fund these medical examinations.
So most of the cases go public when there are already visible MRSA infections in the patient - said the head of the department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict recommendations for the implementation of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological paintings.
Antibiotic therapy should be directed, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance to drugs, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is still less frequent in the case of patients on the outpatients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Saving with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through healthcare.
Therefore, they play a very important role in washing hands, using rubber gloves and masks, but also in this regard there are considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is infected by the transmission of drops and direct contact between persons, but it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient in national hospital conditions.
Moreover, the hospital rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very together, although in order to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, you can also experience - added Karolina Böröcz - that in the less favourable economic situation hospitals saves with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and that is why there is a greater likelihood of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate prevention measures are being implemented, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the infection of the pathogen agent may be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, which is why it is being fought against in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The programme appears to be successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a downward trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
