Fodor and six per cent Hungarian
According to the Minister of Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, meetings at expert level will be completed on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official opening will continue the ministerial negotiations on the post-2012 international climate regime.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world were discussing the Balí Route Sheet, which was available on subsequent efforts to reduce emissions, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, which was in force until 2012.
There are lively discussions on the particular situation between developing countries and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that for the time being it does not want to negotiate on precise figures, although it tends to agree that, compared to the 1990 situation, by 2020, greenhouse gas emissions will fall by 25 to 40 per cent.
Another major theme of the conference is that if industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are or are not willing to provide material and technological assistance to countries that need it.
A further agreement was reached on aid to developing countries.
The support fund provided for in the Kyoto Protocol will be directed by a 16-member management board, probably within the United Nations Global Environment Facility (GEF) - writes "Piac es Profit".
Six per cent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for the Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to preserve its vanguard role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU undertakes to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020, whether or not the "after-2012 agreement" will be signed, and is willing to undertake to reduce even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the signing countries of the 1997 Kyoto Protocol committed to a fall of 5.2 per cent, within which the 15 EU Member States committed to a fall of 8 per cent.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent over the period between 1985 and 87, which our country will meet - points to the press release from the Ministry of the Environment.
That is a lot at stake in Balí, since within two years the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force will be delayed by after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments entered into in the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, whose need was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, the international scientific association of the United Nations dealing with climate change, which received the Nobel Peace Prize.
The reduction of emissions would therefore be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C of the earth ' s average temperature could not be prevented, as scientists believe it would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army Recruited on YouTube
The units of the British army in a video distributor publish recordings about actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First, the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of YouTube services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on helmets are controlled in the general body of Kandahar operations, then sent to London to be loaded on the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been loaded in this way on the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of actions carried out in Iraq and Afghanistan, while both the British Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force had loaded the videos with recruitment goals, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence, they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda is practically nothing compared to conventional recruitment television spots - the expert in defense of the BBC, Gordon Mackenzie, said - in return, inevitably have some political messages, since in a specific way they justify the reason for the military actions decided by the government.
Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the recordings carefully edited and censored, there are also popular videos in the distributor, such as about the death of soldiers: in the films of "official" propaganda, a few hypocrites, officers speak as much of loss, but not the bloody part of the fight.
In addition, many videos recorded in real operations have been uploaded to the Internet from the battle camps in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruiting with video shooting games, downloadable for free, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can directly replace the soldiers.
