Venus: twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most planet like Earth, something that had not yet been raised. The European Venus Express probe discovered rays in the atmosphere and remolines in the poles, the same ones that appear also in winter on Earth.
For three decades the researchers suspected that there might be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the rays are silent at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal Nature.
According to the famous model of Urey-Miller's origin, the rays caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, had given rise to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it's not like this: if there were any days of life there, it would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times greater than on Earth and on the surface at 500°C, so that temperatures can be reached below zero.
"Possible, Venus is a "diabolic" twin of Earth, but still a twin," said Russell.
The main objective of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so much like Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there have been no special missions, just for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles of "Nature", according to researchers' opinion, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighbouring planets have more common characteristics with the Earth than we had assumed," ESA reports.
