This phenomenon recalls the winds in the high atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost as large.
This planet is also called a white star or a vespertin star orbiting around the Sun almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day in Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus, with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars, does not look much like the Earth, scientists assume that both planets had been formed under the same conditions.
On both planets there was abundant water that remained on the Earth in the oceans, but in Venus it was separated into the universe.
While carbon dioxide had become carbon stones in the Earth, Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
